        title: "Structuring Presentations and Business Talks",
        content: "Business presentations and professional talks require a different structure than debate cases. While debate cases are organized around argumentation, presentations should be organized around a narrative arc that guides the audience to a conclusion.\n\nThe most effective presentation structure follows a simple pattern: Hook, Problem, Solution, Evidence, and Call to Action. Your debate training prepares you well for each element, but the proportions differ. In debate, you might spend 80% of your time on argumentation. In a presentation, spend more time on the hook and problem setup, because if your audience does not understand why they should care, no amount of evidence will persuade them.\n\nVisual aids are another key difference. Debate rounds rarely involve slides or visual materials. Business presentations almost always do. The rule of thumb is that your slides should complement your words, not duplicate them. Never read from your slides. Use them for data, images, and key phrases that reinforce your spoken argument. Your ability to speak extemporaneously while referencing key points is a debate skill that translates perfectly here.\n\nThe conclusion of a presentation should be clear and actionable. In debate, you crystallize to show why you win. In a presentation, you crystallize to show what the audience should do next. Whether it is approving a budget, adopting a new process, or simply remembering three key takeaways, end with a specific, memorable call to action.",
