        title: "Evidence in Writing vs. Speaking",
        content: "In oral debate, you often paraphrase evidence and summarize sources quickly. In writing, evidence standards are higher and more precise. Readers can re-read and scrutinize your sources in ways that debate audiences cannot.\n\nDirect quotation is more important in writing than in speaking. When a source says something particularly well or when the exact wording matters, quote it directly and cite it properly. Paraphrasing is acceptable when you are summarizing broader findings, but the key claims should be attributed precisely.\n\nData presentation differs significantly in written arguments. In debate, you might say 'studies show a 40% increase.' In writing, you should specify: 'A 2024 study published in the Journal of Economic Policy by researchers at Stanford University found that financial literacy programs led to a 40% increase in savings behavior among participants (Chen et al., 2024).' The additional specificity builds credibility and allows readers to verify your claims.\n\nCounterargument integration is more nuanced in writing. In debate, you refute opposing arguments in rebuttal speeches. In writing, you weave counterarguments into your text using a structure called the 'turn and response.' Present the strongest version of the opposing view, then explain why your position is still more compelling. This demonstrates intellectual honesty and actually strengthens your argument by showing you have considered and addressed the best objections.",
