        content: "Different types of argumentative writing serve different purposes, and your debate training prepares you for all of them. Understanding the distinctions helps you adapt your approach appropriately.\n\nAcademic essays are the most structured form. They require formal tone, rigorous citation, and systematic development of a thesis. Your debate case structure translates almost directly: introduction with thesis, body paragraphs as contentions, and a conclusion that synthesizes your analysis. Academic writing demands objectivity in tone even when advocating for a position.\n\nOp-eds and opinion pieces are more personal and conversational. They still require strong arguments and evidence, but they also benefit from personal voice, anecdotes, and accessible language. Think of an op-ed as a debate speech written for a general audience. You have roughly 700 to 800 words to make one compelling point, so choose your strongest argument and develop it fully.\n\nPolicy memos and business cases are action-oriented documents. They start with a recommendation, present supporting evidence, address potential objections, and conclude with implementation steps. Your debate training in policy analysis translates directly here. The key difference is that these documents must be concise, scannable, and focused on actionable outcomes.\n\nPersuasive emails are the most common form of argumentative writing in professional life. Every request, proposal, or recommendation you send via email is an exercise in written persuasion. Keep them brief, lead with your ask, provide two or three supporting reasons, and make it easy for the reader to say yes.",
