        content: "In debate, once you deliver your speech, it is done. There is no revision. Writing gives you a powerful advantage that debate does not: the ability to revise, refine, and perfect your argument before anyone sees it.\n\nEffective revision happens in multiple passes. The first pass should focus on argument structure: Is your thesis clear? Does each paragraph support it? Is the logical flow coherent? This is the equivalent of evaluating your case architecture in debate prep.\n\nThe second pass focuses on evidence and reasoning: Is each claim supported? Are your sources credible and properly cited? Does your analysis connect evidence to claims explicitly? Read each paragraph and ask whether a skeptical reader would be persuaded.\n\nThe third pass addresses style and clarity: Are your sentences clear and concise? Is your tone appropriate for your audience? Have you eliminated unnecessary words? Strong writing is lean writing. Cut every word that does not contribute to your argument.\n\nThe final pass is proofreading: grammar, spelling, punctuation, and formatting. These details matter because errors undermine your credibility. A brilliant argument with multiple typos signals carelessness, and readers may question whether your research was equally careless.\n\nOne effective revision technique is reading your work aloud. Your debate training makes this especially powerful because you can hear when a sentence is awkward, when a transition is missing, or when your argument loses momentum. Your ear for spoken argument is a revision superpower.",
