        content: "Critical media consumption is not just about knowing what to look for; it is about building habits that make verification automatic. Your debate preparation habits provide a foundation for these practices.\n\nThe first habit is source checking. Before accepting or sharing any claim, check the original source. News articles often cite studies, reports, or statements. Find the original document and see if the article accurately represents it. This is the equivalent of reading the full evidence card in debate rather than trusting an opponent's characterization of it.\n\nThe second habit is lateral reading. Instead of evaluating a source by looking at the source itself (its design, its 'about' page), open new tabs and see what others say about it. Professional fact-checkers use this technique because a well-designed website can look credible while publishing misinformation. Check if reputable sources cite this organization and whether experts in the field take it seriously.\n\nThe third habit is checking your own reaction. When you feel certain that something is true or outraged by a claim, that is the moment to pause and verify. Strong emotional reactions often indicate that content was designed to provoke rather than inform. Your debate training in emotional regulation helps here: channel the same composure you use in high-pressure rounds to resist the impulse to accept or share unverified claims.\n\nThe fourth habit is updating your beliefs. Good debaters change their position when the evidence warrants it. Apply the same intellectual flexibility to your information consumption. When you encounter credible evidence that contradicts your current understanding, be willing to revise your views. This is not weakness; it is intellectual integrity.",
