        content: "Understanding the taxonomy of problematic information helps you respond appropriately to different types of media challenges.\n\nMisinformation is false or inaccurate information shared without intent to deceive. The person sharing it genuinely believes it is true. This is the most common form of problematic information and often spreads through well-meaning people who do not verify before sharing. The appropriate response is gentle correction with evidence, not accusation or ridicule.\n\nDisinformation is deliberately false information created and spread with the intent to deceive. This includes propaganda, fabricated news stories, doctored images, and coordinated influence campaigns. Disinformation is designed by its creators to exploit cognitive biases and emotional triggers. Your debate training in identifying manipulative argumentation helps you spot these efforts.\n\nMalinformation is true information shared with the intent to harm. This includes taking real facts out of context, revealing private information to damage someone, or presenting accurate but incomplete data to create a misleading impression. Malinformation is particularly tricky because the individual facts may be verifiable even though the overall impression is misleading.\n\nIn all three cases, your debate skills help: evaluate the evidence, check the context, consider the source's motivation, and look at the broader picture before accepting or sharing. The key question is not just 'Is this factually accurate?' but 'Does the way this information is presented create an accurate understanding of reality?'",
